<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ861203-0060 </DOCNO><HL> Crest-Foam Accepts$14.50-a-Share OfferFrom a Partnership</HL><DD> 12/03/86</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> LEG CFOTENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM) </IN><DATELINE> MOONACHIE, N.J.  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Crest-Foam Corp. said its board and majority holders agreed for the company to be acquired by Landamp;P Foam, a partnership consisting of units of Leggett andamp; Platt Inc. and Pacific Dunlop Ltd.    Terms call for Crest-Foam shareholders to receive $14.50 a share in a tender offer that began yesterday. The offer has an indicated value of about $18 million.    Crest-Foam, which employs about 450, makes polyurethane foam used in furniture and bedding and under carpets. Earnings in the fiscal nine months ended Aug. 31 fell 1.2% from a year earlier to $921,000, or 71 cents a share.    Leggett andamp; Platt, based in Carthage, Mo., makes furniture components. Pacific Dunlop is a manufacturing concern based in Melbourne, Australia.    The merger is subject to a minimum of 937,400 shares being tendered. Crest-Foam's two principal holders, who together own 72.5% of the company, have agreed to tender their shares under the offer, which expires at the close of business Dec. 30.    Crest-Foam shares closed yesterday at $14.125, down 62.5 cents, in American Stock Exchange composite trading. </TEXT></DOC>